iabhach</i> ‘brindled’ in Carbery, west Cork."],"variants":[{"name":"McArthy","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cárthaigh</b>, ‘son of <i>Cárthach</i>’. See   McCarthy  ."]},{"name":"McCarty","meanings":["Irish: variant of   McCarthy  , reflecting the common southern Irish pronunciation of <i>th</i>."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}]},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1645–1693":"1645–1693","–1690":"–1690","–1691":"–1691","–Female":"Surnud","1645":"1645","1693":"1693","1691":"1691","1690":"1690","Dunmanway, Cork, Ireland":"Dunmanway, County Cork, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1645–1693":"1645–1693","–1690":"–1690","–1691":"–1691","–Female":"Kuollut","1645":"1645","1693":"1693","1691":"1691","1690":"1690","Dunmanway, Cork, Ireland":"Dunmanway, County Cork, Irlanti"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1645–1693":"1645–1693","–1690":"–1690","–1691":"–1691","–Female":"Décédée","1645":"1645","1693":"1693","1691":"1691","1690":"1690","Dunma